jabohapN jbh jbhh jbhp
jabohapN [The forehead;] the part of the face which is the place of prostration: (As, Msb, K:) or the even part that is between the eyebrows and the naASiyap [or place where the hair grows in the fore part of the head]: (Kh, JK, Msb, K:) so of a man, (S, Msb,) and of others: (S:) [or,] of a horse, the part that is below the ears and above the eyes: (TA:) pl. jibaAhN. (Msb, TA.) ― -b2- [Hence,] Aljabohapu (assumed tropical:) A certain Mansion of the Moon; [the Tenth Mansion;] (S, K, Kzw;) consisting of four stars; (S;) the four stars [ ζ, γ, η, and α,] in the neck and heart of Leo; [regarded by the Arabs as the fore-part, or forehead, of Leo;] (Kzw in his descr. of Leo;) between each of which and the next to it is the space of a whip's length; the northernmost of them called by astrologers AlOasadu. (Kzw in his descr. of the Mansions of the Moon.) ― -b3- Also (assumed tropical:) The moon (K, TA) itself: but [it rather seems to mean the upper part of the disc of the moon; for] it is said in the M that a certain unknown poet has metaphorically assigned a jbhp to the moon. (TA.) ― -b4- Also jabohapN, (tropical:) The chief of a people, or company of men; (JK, Mgh, K, TA;) like as one says the wajoh thereof. (Mgh, TA.) ― -b5- (tropical:) The generous and manly, or manly and noble, persons of a people, or company of men: or men exerting themselves in the case of a bloodwit or a debt or other obligation, (K, TA,) or in repairing the condition of a poor man, (TA,) and who come not to any one but he is ashamed to turn them back, (K, TA,) or who are seldom or never turned back by anyone: so, accord. to Aboo-Sa'eed, in a trad. in which it is said that there shall be no poor-rate in the case of the jbhp. (TA.) ― -b6- (tropical:) A company, or collected number, of men, (JK, S, Msb,) and of horses: (JK, Msb:) or, of horses, the best: (TA:) and [simply] horses; (Lth, S, M, Mgh, K;) a word having no sing., or n. un.: (M, K:) accord. to Lth, (TA,) having this last meaning in the trad. above mentioned; (S, Mgh, TA;) because horses are the best of beasts. (Mgh.) ＝ -A2- (tropical:) Abjectness, or ignominy; (JK, M, K, TA;) and a state of annoyance, or molestation: (Z, TA:) thought by ISd to be from jabahahu meaning “ he encountered him with that which he disliked or hated, ” or “ he accused him thereof to his face; ” because the doing this causes one to experience abjectness, or ignominy. (TA.) It is said to have this meaning in a trad., in which it is said, faUinRa QllReha qado OaraAHakumo mina Aljabohapi wAlsRajRapi wAlbajRapi, i. e. For God hath relieved you from abjectness, or ignominy, &c., and milk diluted with water, and blood drawn
from a vein [of a camel], which the Arabs used to eat: or in this trad., (TA,) Aljabotahapu is the name of a certain idol (ISd, K, TA) that was worshipped in the Time of Ignorance: (TA:) and AlsjRp and AlbjRp were two idols. (S and K in art. sj.)

4 AjiHrhu OjHrh AjHrh AjHrp jHr
4. AjiHrhu He made it (a [lizard of the kind called] DabR [&c.]) to enter its burrow, or hole;
(S, * K;) as also jaHarahu↓: (K:) and it (rain) constrained it (a Daba [&c.]) to enter its burrow, or hole. (A, * TA.) ― -b2- [Hence,] OajoHarahumu AlfazaEu (tropical:) [Fright drove them into their dwellings]. (A.) ― -b3- AjHrt AlsRanapu (tropical:) Drought, or dearth, brought the people into strait, or narrow, circumstances. (A.) ― -b4- And AjHrhu UilaI kacaA (assumed tropical:) He constrained him, or compelled him, to have recourse to, or to betake himself to, or to do, such a thing. (K, * TA.) ＝ -A2- AjHr Alqawomu (tropical:) The people, or company of men, entered upon a time of drought, (K,) and difficulty. (TA.) ― -b2- AjHrt AlnRujuwmu (tropical:) The stars (i. e. the stars of winter, TA) occasioned no rain. (K, TA.)

mujaAnisN mjAns
[mujaAnisN Homogeneous; congenial; similar;
conformable; syn. muXaAkilN. (K.) But IDrd asserts that As used to reject the saying of the vulgar, hecaA mujaAnisu lihecaA [This is homogeneous with this, &c.], and to say, It is post-classical. (S.) [See also 3.]
